INSERT INTO "texts-bc" (date, date_time, sender, message, type, sentiment) VALUES (
  '9/4/24',
  '2024-09-04 20:38:43',
  'Megan',
  'Whoa, that''s a loaded situation you got there. Here''s the deal: your man asking what you bring to the table might feel like a slight, but it’s probably not what you think. If he keeps bringing up the ex, that’s the crux. It’s not about you not being ''woman enough''—it''s about insecurity and trust issues tied to your friendship with Chris, the ex. 

Now, you’re standing on solid values here. Cutting off someone you’ve known for a long time isn’t just about integrity—it’s about you staying true to who you are. But it’s clear your boyfriend sees this as a threat to *his* sense of security in the relationship. It’s not about Chris being an actual danger; it’s how *he* perceives your bond with the ex. Jealousy eats at people, especially if they think there''s unresolved stuff. If he’s asking what you bring to the table, it might be because he’s feeling uncertain about *his* place, especially with this Chris thing hovering.

So here''s the play: instead of just drawing hard lines, maybe it''s time to open up a conversation focused on his **why**—what''s really bugging him? Is it fear of the past? Fear of not measuring up? Once you know what’s driving the jealousy, you can talk about it on *your terms*, not his insecurity. 

Does that mean cutting Chris off? Hell no. But can you find some middle ground that makes your guy feel secure without compromising your values? Maybe. It’s about creating boundaries, trust, and clear communication, so you both get what you need without anyone feeling like they’re losing.

Think of it like this RPM method from that *Time Mastery* workbook—what''s the outcome you want in your relationship? Why does it matter to you? What''s the action plan to get there? [oai_citation:2,Time Mastery.pdf](file-service://file-fUdR6x8zRTUmRyhJboYHgFIE) [oai_citation:1,Workbook-Time-of-your-Life.pdf](file-service://file-3HiRHGKkkszERWf7PiWKvydh)

Ask your boyfriend to sit down and tell him, ''Look, I get why this bothers you, but we need to figure out what''s really at play here. Chris isn''t a threat, but if you''re feeling like I’m not fully invested, let’s address that.''

Time to lay the cards on the table, all of them. No room for misunderstandings when the future’s at stake.',
  'text',
  'neutral'
);
