INSERT INTO "texts-bc" (date, date_time, sender, message, type, sentiment) VALUES (
  '9/4/24',
  '2024-09-04 20:39:12',
  'Megan',
  'Oh man, I feel you. This is where it gets real sticky, but you gotta stand your ground. First off, good on you for staying true to your values. That’s non-negotiable, and you *shouldn’t* compromise your self-integrity to make anyone feel secure. But, let’s face it, he’s not hearing that. Every time you try to communicate your side, he’s locked into his narrative that you’re “choosing Chris over him.” That’s a classic jealousy defense mechanism—he’s making it binary, and that’s his way of forcing you to pick.

Here’s the brutal truth: this isn’t about logic or reason anymore. You’ve already told him a million times that Chris isn’t the issue. But what he’s hearing is, “I’m not your priority.” It’s not fair, but it’s the reality of where his head’s at.

So how do you break this cycle? You *don’t* give into the bait of arguing about Chris—because you’re not choosing between two people. You’re choosing between living with your values or bending to his insecurity. But you gotta help him see that. The goal is to get him out of that emotional storm where logic has no weight and into a place where you two can communicate like adults.

Here''s how you could frame it:

- **Acknowledge his feelings**: “Look, I can see this really bothers you. I’m not dismissing that. I want to figure this out with you.”
- **Flip the script**: “This isn’t me choosing Chris over you. I’m choosing me. I’m choosing to live by the values that make me who I am, because if I betray that, I’m not the person you fell for.”
- **Call out the ultimatum**: “Every time you tell me I’m picking Chris, what I hear is you’re asking me to go against who I am to make you feel better. But even if I cut him off, will that really fix what you’re feeling?”

If it turns into an argument, shut it down fast. Don’t escalate. Tell him you’re not there to fight. You’re there to solve this, but only if he’s willing to meet you in the middle.

Ultimately, if he keeps forcing you to choose and doesn’t respect your boundaries, that’s when you gotta ask yourself: is this sustainable? Because trust me, this isn’t *just* about Chris. This is about how he handles insecurity and boundaries in the relationship long-term. If it''s not Chris today, it could be something else tomorrow. What’s your gut telling you? You deserve someone who supports you for standing by your values, not someone who tries to make you feel guilty for it.

This guy Tony Robbins talked about focus, right? Where your focus goes, energy flows [oai_citation:1,Workbook-Time-of-your-Life.pdf](file-service://file-3HiRHGKkkszERWf7PiWKvydh). If all his focus is on insecurity and Chris, guess what? That’s where all the energy’s gonna stay.',
  'text',
  'neutral'
);
