INSERT INTO "texts-bc" (date, date_time, sender, message, type, sentiment) VALUES (
  '2/26/25',
  '2025-02-26 20:55:00',
  'Megan',
  'Choosing commitment means accepting your partner exactly as they are, despite their flaws. It means never threatening to leave, even if at times you might want to. It also means caring about your partner’s pain as much as, if not more than, your own.

As John so aptly puts it, “If my wife is in pain, my world stops so I can listen to her.” In a committed relationship, you will both stop the world to try to understand and ease each other’s pain. This is partly why we get married, and this is partly why we love.

We need each other, and we need to be needed by each other. True commitment is choosing each other over others. Because ultimately, what makes relationships work is the decision to make them work.

There is one step that cascades toward all betrayals. It often happens when things aren’t going well in the relationship. That step is making negative comparisons between our partner and other real or imagined alternative partners.

We call these negative comps. Rather than nurturing gratitude for what we have with our partner, we nurture resentment for what’s missing. When something bothers us about our partner, rather than discussing it and getting our needs met within the relationship, we fantasize about another relationship and how we might receive what’s missing from our current one.

These negative comparisons become a dangerous way of dealing with dissatisfaction.



Many years ago, John had been working with a couple for several weeks. One night, they arrived at their session and declared they were done. John was the sixth therapist they had seen, and as far as they were concerned, therapy was failing.

John was surprised. He had thought their case was going well.

“Could you do me a favor?” he asked. “Since you’ve already paid for this session, would you be willing to stay and help me understand why my therapy has failed for you? I have a commitment to myself to grow from my failures.”

The couple agreed to stay. John asked them what their weaknesses were.',
  'text',
  'neutral'
);
INSERT INTO "texts-bc" (date, date_time, sender, message, type, sentiment) VALUES (
  '2/26/25',
  '2025-02-26 20:56:55',
  'Megan',
  '“We had a huge argument,” the woman began, but then her husband interrupted to continue the story. “We went to a party, and I was in the middle of a great conversation with a woman I met there. Then my wife tapped me on the shoulder, like she always does, and said she was tired and wanted to go home.”

The husband continued, “On the car ride home, I told her that I had found the woman at the party really attractive, and had really enjoyed talking to her.”

The wife added, “I got angry and told him to grow up and stop flirting with other women.”

John then asked, “And what were you thinking?”

The woman hesitated before answering, “I was thinking that I wished I was with a more mature man, and that I could do better.”

At that moment, John understood why therapy hadn’t worked.

“You can go now,” he told them. “I know my therapy isn’t working. Thank you.”

The couple was stunned. They asked John what he had learned from their argument that made things so clear.

“You two were in love, so you got engaged, got married, bought a house, and had children. But there’s no real commitment in your relationship. You’re always thinking maybe you can do better. You meet a woman at a party and compare her to your wife. You complain, and in response, your wife also thinks she could do better with a more mature man. You’re not really committed.”

The husband protested, “Everything I do is for my family! I sacrifice every day. What do you mean I’m not committed?”

The wife added, “I take care of everything at home and also have a stressful job


Let me tell you the story of Alice in Wonderland, said John. Alice sees this very unusual rabbit go down a hole and she jumps in with two feet.

Alice sees an unusual rabbit and jumps down the hole with both feet. She has no idea what awaits her. Wonderland is full of challenges, fears, and obstacles, but it’s also an adventure. Alice doesn’t hesitate. She doesn’t wait for a better rabbit. She commits to the journey.

“That’s commitment,” John explained. “You two never did that. You have the trappings of commitment—marriage, a house, kids—but in your minds, you keep looking over your shoulder, wondering if you’d be better off with someone else. No therapist can help you until you decide to truly commit.”

A few months later, John checked on them. They had moved, found a new therapist, and were finally talking about trust, loyalty, and commitment. For the first time, they had a fighting chance.

At some point in your relationship, things will get difficult. Your partner will annoy you, hurt your feelings, or let you down. And in that moment, you might wonder if you chose the right person.

Couples who are truly committed don’t have one foot out the door. They don’t entertain the fantasy that someone better is out there. If something is wrong, they talk to their partner—not complain about them to someone else.

Committing to a relationship requires vulnerability. It means asking:

Will they meet my needs?
Will they be there for me?
Will they be there for me?
Will they love me as I am, or try to change me?
Will they betray me?

When we fall in love, we put our best foot forward. But over time, our real selves emerge—imperfections and all. The real magic happens when we realize that our partner truly loves us for who we are, not the idealized version of us.

Trust is the oxygen of a relationship. It’s built in small moments—showing up when your partner needs you, listening with empathy, and thinking for both of you, not just yourself

Commitment is built by believing—and communicating—that your partner is precious and irreplaceable. It’s about magnifying their good qualities and minimizing the bad.

On the other hand, betrayal is nurtured by focusing on what’s lacking in your partner and convincing yourself that they are replaceable.',
  'text',
  'neutral'
);
