INSERT INTO "texts-bc" (date, date_time, sender, message, type, sentiment) VALUES (
  '5/4/25',
  '2025-05-04 20:10:02',
  'Megan',
  'The most accurate way to test how many eggs you have left—aka your ovarian reserve—is a combination of the following:

1. Anti-Müllerian Hormone (AMH) Blood Test

This is the gold standard for assessing ovarian reserve.
	•	What it measures: The level of AMH in your blood, which is produced by follicles in your ovaries.
	•	Why it’s great: AMH levels correlate with the number of eggs you have left.
	•	Pros:
	•	Can be done any day of your cycle
	•	Non-invasive, just a blood draw
	•	Stable levels month-to-month
	•	Limitations:
	•	Doesn’t tell you egg quality, just quantity
	•	Doesn’t predict exact fertility or guarantee pregnancy

2. Antral Follicle Count (AFC) via Transvaginal Ultrasound
	•	What it is: A doctor counts the visible follicles on your ovaries at the beginning of your cycle (typically day 2-5).
	•	Why it matters: More antral follicles = higher ovarian reserve
	•	Best used with: AMH test for a complete picture
	•	Limitation: Operator-dependent (some sonographers are better than others)

3. FSH and Estradiol Levels (Day 3 Blood Test)
	•	What it measures: FSH (follicle-stimulating hormone) and Estradiol on day 3 of your cycle.
	•	Higher FSH = Lower reserve
	•	Why it’s falling out of favor: More variable and less accurate than AMH
	•	Still useful: As a secondary data point

4. Optional: Ovarian Reserve Panel or Fertility Workup

Many clinics offer full hormone panels with LH, TSH, prolactin, etc. for a more holistic view.

⸻

Best Approach:

If you want the clearest picture, do AMH + AFC. That’s like checking both the inventory (AMH) and peeking into the warehouse (AFC).

Think of it this way:
AMH is your stock count. AFC is your warehouse tour. FSH is the assistant manager nervously guessing what’s left.',
  'text',
  'neutral'
);
